                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Jammu, June 22 (PTI): Two teenage sisters from Pakistan-occupied Kashmir crossed into India apparently to escape torture by their stepmother. They have been arrested by the army in Jammu and Kashmir.          ,19, and Sadaf, 17, said they faced regular beatings at home for the past several years, officers claimed.                  
	Srinagar (PTI): Four Lashkar-e-Toiba militants were killed in the Valley on Sunday, two of them in an encounter in Srinagar that also claimed the life of a CRPF jawan. The gunbattle at Shopripora village in Chatterhama, 17km from Srinagar, also left two security personnel, a sub-inspector and a CRPF man, injured.                   
	Srinagar (PTI): A surprise visit by chief minister Ghulam Nabi Azad has led to the suspension of 11 officials, including an assistant executive engineer and two block development officers. These officials were found absent without reason when Azad came visiting on Saturday, sources said.                   
	Varanasi (PTI): The Kashi Vishwanath temple here will soon have a biometric security system with installation of fingerprint scanners at every entrance because of increasing terrorist threats to religious places. Hydraulic gates and X-ray machines will also be the part of the new security set-up, officials said.                  
	Oxford (PTI): Oxford University considers Indian students among the best in the world and would like more of them to join its campus, ch-ancellor Chris Patten has said. We want more Indian students because we want the best in the world to come to Oxford, Patten said. Most of the Indian students are in the Said Business School.                  
	 Silicon Valley (PTI): Over 300 dancers from across the globe gathered here on Sunday to set a world record for the biggest Kuchipudi performance. The performance of the ancient Indian classical dance will take place before Guinness World Records delegates.                                                                                                                         
